dataEntryForms.htmlCode:
Human Health Site Planning and Monitoring 

Does the site provide clinical care to patients?

If Yes, continue with component 1

If No, do not complete component 1; skip to component 2

 

1. Clinical admission assessment, clinical investigation, and use of microbiology results in clinical decision making
Component and sub-components Progress towards sub-component Answer Narrative
a. Clinical admission assessment 1a1 Does the site have guidelines to help clinicians decide which microbiology samples to take from patients?
1a2 Do the guidelines include standardised algorithms to ensure consistency?
1a3 Is patient sampling guided by a standardised admission proforma, including clinical signs and symptoms?
b. Clinical data 1b1 Is a unique alphanumeric identifier (ID number) assigned to patients and so that laboratory results can be linked with the correct patient?

 
1b2 Does the sample request form (whether paper or electronic) record patient gender?
1b3 Does the sample request form (whether paper or electronic) record patient age and/or date of birth?
1b4 Does the sample request form (whether paper or electronic) record whether infection is presumed to be community or hospital acquired?
1b5 How are clinical/patient data included in requests to the microbiology laboratory?
c. Clinical investigation 1c1 On what basis are clinical investigations done at the site?
1c2 Are clinical details recorded on requests to the microbiology laboratory?
1c3 If yes, how are the details recorded?
d. Use of microbiology results in clinical decision-making 1d1 How are microbiology test results provided to requesting clinicians? (If more than one method is used, please detail additional methods in comments)
1d2 Does the site have guidelines to help clinicians decide whether to prescribe antimicrobials, and which antimicrobials to prescribe, on the basis of microbiology test results?
e. Training and quality assurance 1e1 Have all relevant clinical staff received up to date training on clinical admission assessment, clinical investigation, and use of microbiology results in clinical decision-making?
2. General laboratory training and quality assurance
a. Training and quality assurance 2a1 Have all relevant laboratory staff received up to date training for the AMR surveillance-specific standard operating procedures (SOP)?
2a2 Have all relevant laboratory staff received up to date training on internal quality control processes?
2a3

Is the laboratory participating in an accredited External Quality Assessment scheme for bacterial identification and antimicrobial susceptibility testing? 


If yes, please indicate which scheme(s) and give details (e.g. proficiency testing scheme or other form of EQA)
2a4 If yes, has the laboratory participated in an accredited EQA cycle in the last six months?
2a5 If yes, please indicate date
2a6 If yes, please indicate score
2a7

Is the laboratory participating in an accredited proficiency testing scheme for bacterial identification and antimicrobial susceptibility testing? 


If yes, please indicate which scheme (s) and give details (e.g. assays that are assessed)
2a9 If yes, has the laboratory participated in an accredited proficiency testing assessment in the last six months? 
2a10 If yes, please indicate date
2a11 If yes, please indicate score
2a12 Does the laboratory provide EQA to other sites? If yes, please give details (e.g. provides proficiency testing panel, repeat testing of % of isolates)

 

3. Isolate identification and susceptibility testing
AMR surveillance component and sub-components Progress towards sub-component Baseline value Narrative
a. Sample transport 3a1 Does the site have SOPS for sample transport in line with international biosafety standards?
3a2 Have all relevant laboratory staff received up to date training for the sample transport SOPs?
3a3 Is the laboratory following the SOPs to ensure that samples are transported safely?
b. Sample registration 3b1 How are clinical samples registered with the microbiology laboratory?
c. Culture and identification 3c1 Is the laboratory equipped with an automated blood culture system?
Please indicate which other samples the laboratory can process for bacterial culture, identification and susceptibility testing
3c2 Cerebrospinal fluid
3c3 Urine
3c4 Stool
3c5 Pus/pus swabs
3c6 Genitourinary samples for culture of N. gonorrhoea
Please indicate which of the following organisms the laboratory can process for identification and AST
3c7 Streptococcus pneumoniae
3c8 Staphylococcus aureus
3c9 Escherichia coli
3c10 Klebsiella pneumoniae
3c11 Acinetobacter spp
3c12 Salmonella spp
3c13 Shigella spp
3c14 Neisseria gonorrhoea
3c15 Is the laboratory using an automated system to perform bacterial identification?
3c16 If yes, please indicate which system.
3c17 Pseudomonas aeruginosa
3c18 Salmonella enterica serovar Typhi
3c19 Salmonella enterica serovar Paratyphi A
3c20 Neisseria meningitidis
d. Susceptibility testing 3d1 How does the laboratory perform antimicrobial susceptibility testing (AST)?
3d2 Is the laboratory able to perform minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) testing?
3d2.1 Which standard is used for AST?
3d3 Does the site have SOPs for the AST method(s) in use? (if yes, please attach)
3d4 Please attach the SOPs for the AST method(s) in use if available  
e. Training and quality assurance 3e1 Have relevant laboratory staff received up to date training on the sample, organism and AST SOPs for the site?
3e2 Does the laboratory provide training in bacterial identification/AST to other sites?
If yes please give details (including any change since last report)

 

4. Isolate storage and referral to AMR laborator
AMR surveillance component and sub-components Progress towards sub-component Baseline value Narrative
a. Storage of isolates 4a1 How are resistant isolates stored?
4a2 If freezers are used, is the power supply reliable with a backup generator and UPS?
4a3 If freezers are used, are they under a service contract with regular external monitoring of temperature?
4a4 Does the site maintain an up to date inventory of all the isolates stored?
b. Transport to AMR reference / coordinating laboratory 4b1 Are invasive isolates regularly transferred to the AMR reference/coordinating laboratory for biobanking?
4b2 If yes, how frequently are isolates transferred?
c. Training and quality assurance 4c1 Does the site have SOPs for sample referral and transfer to the AMR reference/coordinating laboratory?
4c2 Have relevant laboratory staff received up to date training on these SOPs?

 

5. AMR data review and use
AMR surveillance component and sub-components Progress towards sub-component Status Narrative
a. Data use 5a1 Are AMR data submitted to a national central database (or equivalent)?
5a2 If yes, how frequently are data submitted?
5a3 Does the site have an antimicrobial stewardship (AMS) committee?
5a4 If the site has an antimicrobial stewardship (AMS) committee, what disciplines are represented? (Please select all that apply)

Multiple choice complete? 
5a5 Does the site have an infection prevention and control (IPC) committee?
5a6

Are AMR data from this site shared with any local stakeholders (e.g. with stewardship committees, collaborators etc)?


(Please select all that apply, and please briefly describe any recent changes)

Multiple choice complete? 
5a7

Are AMR data from this site shared with any international stakeholders, e.g regional or global surveillance programs, research collaborators, or others?

(If yes, please describe briefly, including any recent changes)
b. Data linkage 5b How are clinical/demographic data linked to the laboratory AMR results?
c. Data governance 5c Does the site have a formal AMR data sharing policy or agreement in place with the ministry of health and/or national public health institute?
6. Antimicrobial use (AMU) data collection and monitoring
a. Routine AMU data, point prevalence survey (PPS) 6a1 Are AMU data routinely collected at the site?
6a2 What system or variables are used to monitor AMU at the site?
6a3 Has the site participated in a point prevalence survey (PPS) of antimicrobial use in the past 12 months?
